Headlines.Author: Ben Fox
Headlines.Headline: Ameren Executive Baxter to Become New CEO

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ameren Corp. AEE named Warner L. Baxter as its new CEO, replacing Thomas R. Voss, who is retiring from the utility operator. Mr. Baxter will take over on April 24, at which time Mr. Voss will become executive chairman. Mr. Voss will retire from Ameren and the board on July 1, and Mr. Baxter is expected to succeed him as chairman on that date. Effective immediately, Mr. Baxter will succeed Mr. Voss as president and Mr. Baxter was elected to Ameren's board. Since 2009, Mr. Baxter has served as the president and CEO of Ameren Missouri and will keep that position until a successor is named.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Ameren Executive Baxter to Become New CEO

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Fiscal Cliff Talks Yield Hints of Compromise
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Fiscal Cliff Talks Yield Hints of Compromise

PARAGRAPH.#text: Business leaders left the White House surprisingly upbeat after talks with President Obama yesterday. "There was a real sense of optimism that the leadership and the president appeared to be focused on making a resolution that, if it happens, could help unleash even more growth and job creation than perhaps anyone has previously expected," Comcast CEO Brian Roberts told the WSJ. Executives used their face time with the president to push for lower corporate tax rates and some said they'd move fewer jobs offshore with a more competitive corporate tax structure. But they also seemed willing to accept Obama's demand that individual rates for higher earners rise.

Headlines.Headline: Ameren 3rd-Quarter Net Up 31% on Tax Benefit; Narrows Year View

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ameren Corp.'s AEE third-quarter earnings rose 31%, partly due to a tax benefit, while revenue declined more than expected as electric revenue slid. The company also narrowed its full-year core earnings estimate to between $2.35 and $2.45 a share from its August forecast of $2.25 to $2.55 a share. Ameren, which operates electric and gas utilities in Missouri and Illinois as well as a merchant power business, has seen its revenue challenged by lower demand amid warmer-than-normal temperatures and a slow economic recovery.

Headlines.Author: Kristin Jones
Headlines.Headline: Ameren Missouri to Buy Back as Much as $377 Million in Debt

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ameren Missouri, a subsidiary of Ameren Corp. AEE, intends to buy back as much as $377 million in senior notes, and also plans to issue new debt, in a refinancing effort. Ameren operates electric and gas utilities in Missouri and Illinois as well as a merchant power business. Ameren Missouri is planning to buy back a portion of four series of notes coming due between 2018 and 2019 with a total principal outstanding of $1.2 billion. A series of notes coming due in 2018, with a principal amount of $250 million, will have first priority.

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: Ameren 2nd-Quarter Profit Rises 53% on Tax Benefit, Lower Costs

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ameren Corp.'s AEE second-quarter earnings rose 53% as the regional power company received a boost from a tax benefit and overhead costs declined. The company also said a stronger performance at its regulated utilities offset a loss at its competitive merchant generating operations, which have been hurt by industrywide weak prices. For the year, the company raised its per-share earnings estimate by a nickel to $2.25 to $2.55. Ameren, which operates electric and gas utilities in Missouri and Illinois as well as a merchant power business, has seen its revenue challenged by lower demand, weak prices and a sluggish economic recovery.

Headlines.Author: Nathalie Tadena
Headlines.Headline: S&P Raises Outlook On Ameren To Positive On Improving Regulatory Risk

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Standard & Poor's Ratings Services raised its outlook on Ameren Corp. AEE to positive from stable, citing expectations the Midwest utility company's regulatory risk will continue to gradually improve over the intermediate term. S&P, which reaffirmed Ameren's corporate credit rating one level into investment grade at triple-B-minus, said there is at least a one-in-three probability that the company's regulatory risk will continue to improve over the intermediate period. The firm also noted new legislation in Illinois, as well as the Illinois General Assembly's passage of a bill that would lower utilities' target return on equity rate, could potentially reduce the regulatory lag and enhance credit quality.

Headlines.Headline: Illinois Lawmakers Override Veto To Pass $3.2 Bln Smart-Grid Bill

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Illinois lawmakers voted to override the governor's veto of a bill that would allow the state's two large utilities to raise rates for a $3.2 billion upgrade of the state's electrical grid. Exelon Corp.'s EXC Commonwealth Edison utility says its $2.6 billion plan will strengthen the northern Illinois grid from storms and other interference and that it will allow customers to save on their bills and will create thousands of jobs. Ameren Corp. AEE has promised similar benefits to its customers in southern Illinois.

Headlines.Author: Ben Fox
Headlines.Headline: Ameren Offers Voluntary Retirement To 715 Employees

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Ameren Corp. AEE said it is offering voluntary retirement packages to about 715 employees, as the Midwest power company cited lower retail electric rates in Missouri and a challenging economy. The employees account for about 13% of the work forces of the units affected, Ameren Missouri and Ameren Services Co. "This program is part of our continued efforts to create an organization that can operate effectively in an environment where demand for energy has softened, costs are rising and our reimbursement for those costs in rates continues to lag," said Ameren Chief Executive Thomas R.

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: Ameren Raises Quarterly Dividend By 3.9%

PARAGRAPH.#text: Ameren Corp.'s AEE board authorized a quarterly dividend increase of 3.9%, joining a growing list of companies returning cash to their shareholders. The Midwest power company's shares were up 2.1% at $30.55 in recent trading, more than the broader market advance. The quarterly dividend was increased by 1.5 cents a share to 40 cents, raising the company's quarterly payout by an estimated $3.6 million. The stock is up 8.4% this year. President and Chief Executive Thomas R. Voss attributed the dividend increase to steps the company has taken "over the last few years to strengthen our financial performance and position.

Analysts aren't expecting major surprises, since the fourth quarter sits between periods of more volatile demand in the summer and winter. Deutsche Bank estimates a 2% decline from a year ago for the power companies it tracks. But declines will vary, with some companies posting higher earnings as rate increases take effect. Investors will look for insight on whether power demand is recovering after two years of declines. The outlook for power prices, which have been curbed significantly by lower natural gas prices, remains an open question as well.

FNEG, a group of investors, wants to install the reactors to provide low-carbon power to the central valley's agricultural industry and to help California meet growing electricity demand while reducing its emissions of carbon dioxide, Areva said in a statement.

Headlines.Author: Mark Peters
Headlines.Headline: POWER POINTS:Utilities To Rely Less On Bank Credit Facilities

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Thursday.) By Mark Peters Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--U.S. power companies are expected to rely less on traditional bank lending in the years ahead as costs rise and availability shrinks. The utility sector continues to access the bond and equity markets for most of its capital needs. Yet as bank credit lines expire, companies may curb their use of the facilities or be forced to seek out other options. The change is part of the ongoing fallout from widespread upheaval in the financial sector as the banks that remain tighten the reins on lending, charging power companies more and providing loans for shorter periods.

Headlines.Author: Steve Goldstein
Headlines.Headline: BEFORE THE BELL: US Stk Futures Mixed Before Beige Book

#text: By Steve Goldstein U.S. stock futures were mixed on Wednesday as the Federal Reserve is due to release its assessment of an economy where output has stabilized but credit remains tight. S&P 500 futures were up 0.3 point to 1025.40 and Nasdaq 100 futures fell 2.5 points to 1652.80. Futures on the Dow Jones Industrial Average slipped 3 points. U.S. stocks rose Tuesday after a three-day break, as Kraft Foods Inc.

launched an unsolicited $16.7 billion bid for Cadbury and the dollar weakened, triggering gains for commodities, stocks and other dollar-based assets, notably gold, which was above $1,000 an ounce for much of the day.

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: Ameren May Boost Share Count 10% With Stock Sale

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Ameren Corp.

said it plans to offer at least 19 million shares of common stock as it plans to use the proceeds to invest in its rate-regulated utility subsidiaries. Shares were down 3.2% at $25.50 in after-hours trading. The company has about 213 million shares outstanding and the company, which operates electric and gas utilities in Missouri and Illinois, said the planned offer would dilute this year's earnings by up to 6 cents this year.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Ameren May Boost Share Count 10% With Stock Sale

Headlines.Author: Kathy Shwiff
Headlines.Headline: Ameren Offers Buyouts To 350 Older Workers, More Cuts Likely

#text: Ameren Corp.

said it offered buyouts to about 350 employees, 3.5% of its work force, and plans to cut more jobs amid reduced power demand. The buyouts are open to full-time employees who will be 58 years old or older as of Dec. 31. The program excludes senior executives and about 60 others. The energy-holding company will give eligible employees its standard management severance of a lump-sum payment of two weeks of pay for each full year of service, with a minimum of 13 weeks and maximum of 52 weeks of pay.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Ameren Offers Buyouts To 350 Older Workers, More Cuts Likely

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Correction

#text: An Aug. 6 MarketWatch report on Ameren Corp.'s

second-quarter earnings decline of 20% incorrectly attributed part of its profit loss to lower merchant power prices. The company's core earnings were not significantly affected because of forward physical and financial hedges, a company spokesman said.

Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: Ameren 2Q Falls 20%, Plans Billions In Cost Cuts

#text: Ameren Corp.'s

second-quarter profit dropped 20% on prior-year hedging gains, but core earnings beat expectations thanks to higher utility rates. Chief Executive Thomas R. Voss also said the energy holding company has found $2 billion of potential cost cuts to reduce capital spending for the next four years. The company is "carefully evaluating projects that may be eliminated or deferred to help our customers manage their costs in these tough economic times and further strengthen our financial profile," Voss said.

Headlines.Author: Cassandra Sweet
Headlines.Headline: Mercury Emissions Up Among 50 US Coal-Fired Pwr Plants-Study

PARAGRAPH.#text: SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones)--Mercury emissions are on the rise from older U.S. coal-fired power plants, according to a study released Thursday. Fifty coal-fired power plants in Texas, Pennsylvania, Alabama, Georgia and eight other states produced more emissions of mercury in 2007 than they did the previous year, according to the study, by the Washington-based Environmental Integrity Project. Together, the plants emitted 20 tons of mercury in 2007. While most of the plants produced more mercury emissions in 2007 year over year, some of them produced fewer of those emissions, said the not-for-profit group, which advocates for stiffer enforcement of environmental laws.

Headlines.Author: Cassandra Sweet
Headlines.Headline: Ike Wreaks Havoc On Texas, Ohio, Midwestern Power Systems

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) By Cassandra Sweet and Mark Peters Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones)--Millions of Americans remained in the dark Monday, as utilities from southern Texas to northern Ohio worked to restore power lost after Hurricane Ike hit the Texas coast and swept north, toppling trees, taking out power lines and damaging utility poles and other equipment. More than 4 million utility customers lost power over the weekend, after Ike made landfall Saturday, flooding Gulf Coast communities and leaving a destructive path from Louisiana to central Texas.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Ike Wreaks Havoc On Texas, Ohio, Midwestern Power Systems

Headlines.Author: Cassandra Sweet
Headlines.Headline: Winds From Ike Ravage Ohio; Hit Ill, Ind, Mo, Ky, Ark

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds Ohio governor's state of emergency declaration, additional Indiana outage numbers) SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones)--Millions of people were still without power in Texas on Monday after Hurricane Ike swept through over the weekend, but several million more lost power in Ohio and other Midwestern states, where high winds upended trees, snapped thousands of power lines and caused widespread damage. At least 2 million utility customers in Ohio lost power Sunday, after the remains of Hurricane Ike roared through, upending trees, snapping power lines and scattering debris with winds of 75 miles per hour and faster.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Winds From Ike Ravage Ohio; Hit Ill, Ind, Mo, Ky, Ark

PARAGRAPH.#text: ST. LOUIS (AP)--Much of the nation continued to sweat Tuesday under oppressive heat, made worse by high humidity, that stretched from the Midwest to the East Coast. Temperatures soared above 90 degrees Fahrenheit, and in some cases above 100 degrees, a trend expected to continue through the weekend in parts of the South and Midwest. The National Weather Service issued excessive-heat warnings in several states, and health officials urged people and pets to stay in air conditioning. Three deaths were blamed on the heat, and the nation's biggest public utility said its 8.7 million customers set an all-time peak record for power consumption Monday.

Headlines.Headline: Rubin sees 'solid growth' despite Asia

STRONG:
"While
        there are specific dimensions in each of these (IMF) programs that could be debated, I am
        confident that (they) ... are the best and probably the only viable way to help these
        countries re-establish stability and confidence."
#text:
WASHINGTON (CBS.MW) -- The U.S. economy is heading for solid growth and
    low inflation this year despite the "real but moderate" effect the Asian crisis
    has had on America, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Wednesday.
    
    Rubin said global recovery will be based on international changes in reaction to this
    crisis. He called Japan to strengthen its banking system and for Europe to institute
    structural reforms so they could play a larger role as an engine of world economic growth.

"Thus far the effects on our economy, though real, are relatively moderate and
    the most likely scenario for the next year is continued solid growth and low
    inflation," Rubin said in a speech at Georgetown University.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Rubin sees 'solid growth' despite Asia
